===''Twenty Years'' retrospective (2008)===
The first major retrospective of Emin's work was held in [[Edinburgh]] between August and November 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgalleries.org/whatson/exhibition/5:368/5118/5426|title=National Galleries of Scotland − What's On − Tracey Emin|publisher=Nationalgalleries.org|date=9 November 2008|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> attracting over 40,000 visitors, breaking the [[Scottish National Gallery of Modern Art]]'s record for an exhibition of work by a living artist.<ref name="theherald.co.uk">{{cite web|author=Phil Miller, Arts Correspondent |url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/news/news/display.var.2465953.0.emin_gives_75_000_sculpture_as_thankyou_for_scots_show.php|title=Emin gives £75,000 sculpture as thank-you for Scots show |work=Herald Scotland|date=6 November 2008|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref>

The large-scale exhibition included the full range of Emin's art from the rarely seen early work to the iconic ''My Bed'' (1998) and the room-sized installation ''Exorcism of the Last Painting I Ever Made'' (1996). The show displayed her unique appliquéd blankets, paintings, sculptures, films, neons, drawings and monoprints. The [[Scottish National Gallery of Modern Art]] was the only UK venue for the show which travels to the Centro de Arte Contemporáneo in [[Málaga]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitecube.com/news/132|title=News – White Cube|author=White Cube|publisher=}}</ref> Spain and then to the Kunstmuseum in Bern, Switzerland from 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kunstmuseumbern.ch/index.cfm?nav=1245,1397,1442&SID=2&DID=9&aID=227|title=Kunstmuseum Bern &#124; Schweiz – Upcoming|publisher=Kunstmuseumbern.ch|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref>

It was reported on 6 November 2008 that Emin gifted a major sculpture to the [[Scottish National Gallery of Modern Art]] as a "thank you"<ref>[http://www.nationalgalleries.org/aboutus/press/1:172 Press release dated 5 November 2008 'Tracey Emin Gifts Major Sculpture as Visitors Have a Last Chance to See Record Breaking Exhibition']</ref> to both the gallery and the city of [[Edinburgh]]. The work called ''Roman Standard'' (2005) comprises a {{convert|13|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} bronze pole, surmounted by a little bird, cast in bronze. The work has an estimated value of at least £75,000.<ref name="theherald.co.uk"/>

